Review:
I would recomend this game only if you want something cheap and a singleplayer dinosaur "simulator" experience (stopping to think now, I think many of these recent dinosaur simulator games are multiplayer, having something that is singlerplayer, like this one, I think is good). This game sure has some improvements if compared to the frist one, but it also have the same problems of the frist game:

- The game doesn't have a tutorial, which can be a problem to new players;

- I think the game could have some type of minimap,  because I got lost many times while trying to find the pods (Just to not get lost, I always walk across the edge of the map);

- The Scan seems to do nothing, it doesn't show me food or water, making me to find these myself;

- The new way to unlock the dinosaurus I think is cool (in the older one, you would need to find the Mutant version of the dinosaur, then kill it, and then you would unlock it. Thanks to that method, I've never unlocked the Therizinosaurus, because the map feels all the same). In this sequel, now to unlock new dinosaurus, you need to destroy a certain amount of pods. I like this, but then again, since the map feel the same, I think is somewhat hard to find these pods;

- The dinosaurus in this game will chase you for the rest of their lifes. You can only escape them by fighting them or using a really fast dinosaur, like the desert version of Appalachiosaurus (one of the stater dinosaurus, and the desert version already come along with it), if you spam the jump (which is the Left Alt by default) with it, you can basically escape from everything. This guy is also a good way to travel in the maps;

- This game explain its lore, but for some reason, you can find the lore of this game only in the description of the game in the Steam page, because in the game itself, never explains the lore, the pods and the mutants just exists.

For the pros, it does have some new dinosaurus, like Megalosaurus, Allosaurus, Kentrosaurus and, the one I liked the most (just because it is brazilian) Oxalaia. 
The game now have Alpha and Apex versions for some dinosaurus, which have a significant better stats than the normals ones (or worse, as the moment I'm writing this, I just got the Alpha Plateosaurus, and it is almost a better Plateosaurus, but it is slower than the normal one). 
The way the camera is positioned reminds me of Disney's Dinosaur PC/PS2 game, which I like it.

I have no idea if the developer of this game will keep woking on it, since he/she is woking in a other dinosaur game (Dinosaurs Dominion), but I think is game is good just to have a little fun.

Edit: I just finished the game, and after I've destroy all the pods, I have unlocked the final map, which is a boss battle against a big mutant Tiktaalik (an animal that is the transition from fish to amphibian) and a giant pod, the Mother Pod, which is just a larger pod with more health. And after I had beaten the Tiktaalik and destroyed the Mother Pod, I just won the game, I didn't even get any reward, which I think is a shame, because I have spend 7,2 hours playing this game (I've spend that many hours just trying to find the pods, even with the help of the desert Carnotaurus, which I think it is the fastest dinosaur in the game).
